# Rules Index

## Behavioral Guardrails

- ÔŁî Never commit, push, or create docs unless explicitly requested
- ÔŁî Never create new git branches unless explicitly requested by the user
- Ôťů Prefer self-explanatory code via naming and structure

## Git workflow (must follow)

These rules are about side effects on the repository. Read-only operations
(`git status`, `git diff`, `git log`, `gh pr view`, `gh run view`, etc.) are
always fine.

### Branch creation

- ÔŁî **Do NOT run `git checkout -b`, `git switch -c`, `git branch <name>`** or
  any equivalent that creates a new local branch unless the user has clearly
  asked for it (e.g. "create a branch", "open a PR", "make a feature branch").
- ÔŁî Do not create a branch "to be safe" or "to follow the project's release
  guide" without asking first. If the working tree is dirty on `main` and you
  need to commit, **ask the user** whether to: (a) commit on `main`,
  (b) create a branch + PR, or (c) stash and continue without committing.
- Ôťů When the user explicitly authorizes a branch, prefer the project's
  existing naming convention (look at `git log --pretty=format:'%d' -20` to
  spot patterns like `codex/...`, `feat/...`).

### Commits and pushes

- ÔŁî Never run `git commit`, `git push`, or `git push --force*` without
  an explicit request from the user.
- ÔŁî Never amend commits that are already pushed unless the user asks for
  it (and warn about the force push that will be required).
- ÔŁî Never run `git reset --hard`, `git clean -fdx`, `git rebase` (interactive
  or otherwise) on the user's working tree without consent.
- Ôťů When the user asks to "save", "commit", "push", or "send to GitHub":
  1. Run `git status` first and **only stage the files explicitly tied to
     the current task** ÔÇö never `git add -A` / `git add .` blindly. Untracked
     files and modifications from other unrelated work must stay out.
  2. Show the user what will be committed (`git diff --staged --stat`) before
     creating the commit.
  3. Follow the conventional commit style observed in `git log`.

### Pull requests

- ÔŁî Never open, close, merge, or rebase a PR (`gh pr create`, `gh pr merge`,
  `gh pr close`) unless the user explicitly asks for that specific action.
- ÔŁî Never run `gh pr merge --admin` (admin override of required checks)
  without an explicit confirmation, even if the user previously asked to
  merge. CI failures unrelated to the current PR must be flagged to the
  user with options before bypassing checks.
- Ôťů Reading PR state (`gh pr view`, `gh pr checks`, `gh run view`) is
  always allowed.

### Working tree safety

- ÔŁî Never delete or modify files outside the scope of the current task
  (e.g. files the user is editing in another frente that show up in
  `git status` but were not part of your work) without asking.
- Ôťů When restoring state with `git stash`, always `pop`/`apply` back at the
  end so the user does not lose pending work.

## Rules (single source of truth per topic)

### Generic (reusable)

- **`general_rules.mdc`**: core coding principles (readability, duplication, docs/comments policy)
- **`clean_architecture.mdc`**: layer boundaries and dependency direction (generic)
- **`coding_style.mdc`**: Dart language/style (naming, formatting, imports, modern Dart, logging, codegen)
- **`null_safety.mdc`**: sound null-safety guidelines and patterns
- **`solid_principles.mdc`**: SOLID principles with examples
- **`flutter_widgets.mdc`**: widget construction/performance patterns (composition, const, lists, layout, theming tokens)
- **`ui_ux_design.mdc`**: desktop UI/UX principles (Fluent vs Material policy, navigation, a11y, responsive desktop)
- **`testing.mdc`**: unit/widget testing conventions (AAA, naming, isolation, mocking)

### Project-specific (`backup_database`)

- **`project_specifics.mdc`**: decisions specific to this repo (Clean Architecture + DDD, dependencies, desktop specifics)
- **`architectural_patterns.mdc`**: consolidated DRY helpers and anti-patterns from audit waves (`RepositoryGuard`, `AsyncStateMixin`, `ByteFormat`, `_safeNotifierCall`, common bug recurrences), plus **┬ž8 Design system** (tokens, `context.colors`, composition) and **┬ž9 Hexagonal / generic SGBDs** (base repo, `GenericDatabaseBackupStrategy`, `registerSgbd`; ADRÔÇĹ004). **Read this BEFORE adding new repositories, providers, orchestration services, or shared UI** to avoid reintroducing eliminated boilerplate.

## Copying to other projects

See `README.md` in this folder. Keep generic rules, and replace `project_specifics.mdc` + `architectural_patterns.mdc` (the latter is project-specific to the helpers in `lib/core/`, `lib/application/providers/`, and `lib/infrastructure/repositories/`).
